segments.text: Y'all did not get married before the war?
It was five years before we got married.
We dated five years, and he was in the Marine Corps at Camp Felton.
And I taught a year of school, and then I got on the American airline and flew out to California, and we got married, and we thought we'd be together six weeks.
And they had the problem with the landing boats out in the marshals on the coral reefs, and they had to redesign the landing boats
And so we lived in Laguna Beach for six months.
And he left, I think, on January 44.
Went to Maui was the first landing they had.
I think that's the name of it.
How many landings did he make with the Marines?
Two or three.
Saipan is where he was hit with a grenade.
He was wounded, I don't know how, where was he injured?
Well, he got a hand grenade in his lungs and he had one under the bone here and the scar always vibrated.
How that didn't cut his tubular vein, I don't know.
and stand up and go in and pull these out of his lungs.
And there was some they never could get that they watched for years.
But it was a Japanese tag in the tree that's written through his name.
And he was evacuated.
And I heard from him 40 days after he went into combat.
He always told me he would never get a letter after he went into combat.
He always would get a letter from a dead man.
So there are 40 days that you didn't hear anything.
But I didn't hear anything.
But on Monday, when the battle was over, I told my father I would hear from him that week.
And my sister got a letter at the post office and ran all the way home.
So I got ready to cry.
It was a hard week.
And my daddy came in.
He had asked me early.
He was going off with the telegrams.
He had asked them when they had a death telegram, could he go?
Because one woman had been given one that her son died, her only child had died, and she was in an office in a building all by herself all day.
They just went up and handed it.
And so I went down and handed my letter to my father.
He didn't want me hearing something without him being there.
And I handed it to him, and he handed it back to me.
I said, Jack's alive.
I didn't say Jack's injured.
Jack's alive.
And he said, you'll have to read it to me, I can't see it.
And I looked and he was crying.
And Jacket was already in the hospital then in Hawaii.
And they always talk about Roosevelt not letting anybody see him in a wheelchair.
He came into their hospital in a wheelchair.
He came to this, didn't he?
Franklin Roosevelt did.
In Hawaii.
Don't you think that's interesting?
You bet.
They always said that he never would allow himself to be.
But these real veterans saw him in a wheelchair.
That's it.
Now, Dr. Williams was in the hospital about how long?
Forgotten by now.
He was alive and excellent.
See, I got to know other people that didn't get to the hospital where they lost their husbands.
And so, you know, we were a group.
We partied together, you know, and they got home.
Right.
About when did he get home?
When did you all get back together?
The war was over.
And, you know, you had to have so many points to be out.
Well, they kept reducing the points.
And I was teaching school, and I gave him notice because he couldn't come to me.
home from the war and come to Redford, Virginia while his wife kept teaching school.
So I gave him notice and he kept moving up the time.
And so finally I met him in Roanoke and I had reserved us a hotel room in Roanoke.
But the next day we got up and got on the bus and went to his mother and daddy's home.
But his brother had brought his mother over for dinner that night.
She couldn't wait till the next day.
And I didn't think, I hadn't thought that would be cruel.
for him to get off the plane and let's have a place to sleep that night over there.
We held that room for a week with his luggage in there, stuff he brought back.
And we only stayed that first night.
We were out visiting our two families with pen men on the room in the hotel.
And I said to him, now, this is an interesting thing.
If you're going to be a lawyer, let's go to Harvard.
Let's go to the best.
He said, no, I'm going to go into education.
Men are needed in high schools.
And he had learned from that short period of time that it took a man to have the discipline that was needed in high schools.
See, that's what's wrong now with the school.
It's not the teachers.
It's not the classroom.
It's the students.
It's the lack of discipline.
How did you all happen to end up at Emory instead of some other school?
Why Emory University?
He had a good friend that was a graduate of Emory.
And he knew it as a method of school.
He always went to private schools, so he taught in .
But Charlie was a good friend of his in Hawaii.
And Charlie was an Emory graduate.
And I think that had an influence on him.
He probably said, that'd be a good school to get a degree in.
And he just announced, no, I'm going to Emory, and I'm going to go into education.
But his professor said, no, you can't.
Now, how long were y'all at Emory before you came to Clemson?
From March 23rd or something like that of 40, I have to count those years back then.
I told you we came in August of 48, didn't I?
We came to Clemson.
And that meant this would have been 46.
We came in March, and we left in August of 48.
So we were on the Emory campus in a trailer for all that time.
He got a master's degree.
And we didn't incur to us that it was anything.
We didn't invite his parents.
They had come to Quantico to see him be commissioned.
And when he got his doctorate, he went back to Emory.
Now, the GED, was there a GED scholar?
GRE.

There was something that, when we were ready to go to Emory, one of his Emory professors was on that board and told Jack to meet him at the train station and wanted him to take one, but he waited to go to LSU or to Columbia in order to get this scholarship or graduate degree.
And Jack said no, he knew what he was getting into.
I think that's a graduate record exam.
I think that is.
Anyway, this Emory professor had him
come to meet him at the train, and tell him that he wanted to have one.
And Jack said no.
And that he knew what he was getting into with Emory.
So he went back to Emory.
Or maybe the first time, I don't know.
But anyway, I think Charles Harris influenced him.
And that's the only thing I know, because he just knew where he was going to do what he wanted to do.
He didn't consult me.
So y'all came here in the fall of 48, and you're here until?
And then to Austin for two years, to Tennessee for two years, and then to Texas in November, to Texas A&M in November 1, 1970.
When did you get to College Station?
Did he precede you?
I came in January.
OK.
I had to sell a house.
You had to sell a house.
And we had to work at a place to leave Mary with some relatives, but she could finish out of school.
When you came, what were your goals as the university president's wife?
Well, I didn't feel like they had changed from anything I had been here when he was vice president.
I didn't have the same title, but I never got excited over any change.
Isn't that terrible?
I just took everything as it came and did the best I could.
And everything included what?
Whatever came.
Well, if we were to meet somebody for a meeting or we were to get on the plane and go someplace or if he called and said, I'm bringing somebody by the house, make a reservation at the restaurant.
I was just running my home like I always did and doing whatever came along and going to what came along.
I didn't feel like that I was anything.
I was just Jack's wife.
How many nights did you all have unscheduled?
Well, that would have varied, but we didn't have one.
He had a full schedule.
I could go pull out those little black books and show you how busy he was.
And then he joined the boards.
He was on several boards and he had those meetings too.
And he did buy me some stock.
So I could go to the meetings.
I'm trying to think of what.
I'll tell you in a minute.
They were cotton.
Oh, Anderson Clayton?
Anderson Clayton.
And he bought me 100 shares of Anderson Clayton so I could go to the stock meetings.
But I didn't go to the stock meetings when he went to Dallas.
And before he left there, they asked him to be on one of the bank boards, national bank boards.
And he came in and said they asked me to be on the grant board.
And I said, I don't know what to tell him about this town.
He didn't want to really do anything with it.
And I said, well, you already have a conflict with the December meetings because he was on enough boards in Dallas that he really did.
And so I gave him an answer.
But Anderson-Clayton was a good association for him.
Do I remember his playing golf sometimes as a relaxation?
Well, I did that.
When we lived at Knoxville, I had said, we're living here, and there are all these resorts up here in the mountains, and it's time.
The children are going to get gone, and we can just have a good time, and we should play golf.
So I went over to the club and arranged for us to take lessons.
He was in Memphis part of the time, and he was in Knoxville part of the time.
So he didn't get all the lessons.
But there came a time when we had secondhand clubs to start with, when he said go on out and start.
And we did.
And that's what got Jack into building, redoing the golf course at Texas A&M.
He'd gotten interested in golf.
And he had plans for a second golf course, mentally.
I heard him say that he thought they should build, that A&M should have another golf course that wasn't enough for that size student body.
But of course he didn't live to see that happen.
But that's how he felt about coffee.
You know, you're competing with yourself.
I played with him when I was so cold that the tears would flow and he'd say, let's play the black nine.
And I wouldn't tell him I was too cold to play, but I played.
I just turned my head so he wouldn't see that I was crying.
When you all were in College Station, what did you do for relaxation?
Nothing exceptional.
I just lived a normal life and read and did what I had to do with my daily chores.
Time passed.
Time passed.
I didn't ever have any time on my hands.
And let's say y'all were members of the A&M Methodist, you attended the Methodist church there.
Y'all have been, were you both lifetime Methodists?
Jack was.
He joined us.
The Baptist church, he didn't belong to a church.
He joined the church in Emory University.
Oh, I see.
His grandfather was a primitive Baptist.
I see.
But he went to church, but not regularly.
He was not a regular church member.
Oh, going up.
Oh, I see.
At one time, one of our ministers stopped, told him he was being moved, and he called Jack and said, I have to talk to you before I leave.
Would you meet me in...
on the campus.
And Jack went down there and he said, I can't leave until I tell you you should go in the ministry.
Jack had worked in the church.
He'd been chairman of the board.
He'd taught students.
Now, by what age was he then?
It was when we lived here.
Oh, here at Clemson?
Yeah, here at Clemson.
Oh.
And Jack had worked in the church.
had taught the students, and then he was teaching later on.
He taught his senior adult class.
And he did whatever came along with it, but he never belonged to anything very long before he was an officer.
He had a way of sort of keeping things running smoothly, I think it was.
I think it was a talent.
Of all of the things he did, all of the different tasks, here
Houston, Tennessee.
No, no, not going to ask the negative.
What do you think he enjoyed the most?
Well, he had friends he enjoyed, but he enjoyed taking his children on a vacation trip.
He enjoyed being home.
All right, but then professionally.
Professionally.
Which of his professional accomplishments or tasks do you think he enjoyed most?
He never talked about it.
I was wondering what?
He was just a happy person.
Was he happiest teaching or administering?
I would say it would be teaching.
I cried the last time he taught class.
I think Lynn actually wrote about it.
That was here at Clemson.
I realized that he loved teaching, he was good at it.
Was there a course that you think he enjoyed most?
No.
He didn't talk about his work.
This makes it hard for me because he didn't, I remember one day he came in and said, he held a meeting with his faculty staff
He disagreed with what they thought they should be doing.
His idea was different.
He went back the next day, called them together, and told, you all are right and I'm wrong.
I've thought it over.
And they were amazed that they couldn't believe that anybody would ever admit that they'd been wrong.
And when there came a time once, one dean, this is like the hard thing, one dean had to go down for a gang arrest.
And he appointed one of his good friends.
And he died.
So the good friend was the acting dean.
But Jack didn't feel like he was the one that should have the job permanently.
And the acting dean was a good friend of Jack's dean of his school.
Jack is the academic dean now.
But he said the acting dean was lazy.
And in spite of having to say no to Dean Hunter's best friend, he hired another man, brought another man in.
And he's been honored and honored and honored.
He was so great.
Rather than just somebody just being inherited through friendship.
And that isn't easy to do.
The old timers, in other words.
at the end of a work day, how could you tell it had been a good day or not a good day for him?
I think it's just routine to have him come home and very seldom ever say anything for a comment.
Anyway, he just acted like he was glad to be home.
And the dog in the oxbow told him he was coming.
The dog would hear the car, bang the floor with his table,

look at me, keep looking at me, and Jack would drive up in the garage, and the dog and I would go to the door, and I would stick my head up for a kiss right here, and the dog would put his paws up on Jack's knee, and Jack would pat his head.
That was our routine.
The dog knew.
And when Jack was in the hospital, you know, we had fired Willie, this same dog, and Willie came back to the house while Jack was in Houston with him there.
Juanita was still there.
The dog carried on so that one of them said she had to put the dog out of the house.
He went with Willie in the car once, and he'd even never go near Willie again.
He didn't like it, instinctively.
Isn't that interesting?
Let's see.
You've got enough for me.
No, no, no.
I can't talk about what Jack thought or did or felt, because when we were home, it was just home, and it wasn't work.
OK, now you see, that's an important characteristic, though, that I'm glad to get in here.
You're saying that, by and large, he kept any worries, frustrations, and or exuberances, that he kept those comparatively quiet.
Which is bad.
If there's stress and you know that there's a bad gene in your family, it's bad to get taken that kind of work.
I know a question.
And there were people that were very stressful that he had to associate with.
All right.
What was his technique if he needed to make a key appointment?
How did he go about trying to identify the appropriate person for that task?
Well, he didn't consult me.
I consulted him a few times.
No, I don't know.
He didn't appoint a search committee.
He didn't?
No.
I guess he inquired, and part of it was,
He was doing his homework.
He was doing his homework, but he wasn't making a big issue of it.
With whom did he inquire?
I don't know.
See, I think that his technique was to talk directly to people that he knew would give him a true answer, people that he really knew.
That's why you and McCauley were good friends, because he knew he could trust him with any answer.
He doesn't want a yes man.
And I think he did his homework always.
Also, when he got to Texas A&M, he had a lot of experience.
He had worked up here through being president of the faculty senate.
It was the biggest honor he ever had.
He told me that the biggest honor I've ever had was being elected by my peers to be a member of the first faculty senate.
I'm glad you put that in there.
See, that's exactly the kind.
Well, that was what happened.
He was a member of the very first faculty senate, and he said that was the greatest honor he'd ever had.
Alright, now, y'all were here when Harvey Gant, the first black student, came to enroll here.
Do you remember anything you can share about those days?
Yeah.
They knew the problems that were going on in Arkansas and Alabama and so forth.
They worked.
They made it
They worked out a schedule.
They had a highway patrolman at every intersection from where Harvey was coming from until he entered the campus.
They allowed the national press to be in the hotel, but not on the campus.
And they brought Harvey up with a highway patrol escort, took him in, set him up in the Google architecture or wherever he was, and that was it, period.
And Harvey had a wonderful sense of humor.
And when things weren't going his, you know, if the students said anything to him, they'd give him all this freshman jobs to do.
He said, you all just keep doing that to me, and I'll sit by you in the cafeteria.
Which he showed you what a fine person he was.
They did not allow a reporter on campus.
I asked Dr. Williams one day about that, and I asked him, well, you mean there wasn't a single incident
And as I recall, he said that when Harvey walked into the field house to register, two sophomore white male students said, where everybody could hear, here comes the coon.

He said two Clemson campus police took those two young men to their room, watched them while they packed their bags, and took them to the county line and said, if you ever set foot in this county, you're under arrest.
We're not going to tolerate that.
And he said...
It may have happened, see, but he wouldn't have come home and told me all of that.
See the difference?
Yeah, he said there was no problem at all, and he said there was careful planning by all kinds of people.
And that day, he had one person that was a member of our supper club who stood up out on the steps of his building and watched all this taking place, and Jack didn't have any use for him after that.
Oh.
Because he was supposed to have gone about his business, about being out watching what was going on.
A member of the faculty.
And as far as he was concerned.
Now, Jack didn't like everybody.
You know that.
He could be nice to people, but he didn't.
I could tell you how the supper club, the three people, the three men he liked.
He associated with them all for all those years.
There were 12 families in it.
He just had the entertainment.
I could...
But he liked people with a sense of humor, that he could joke with and be friends with.
And I think that's why he liked book wires so much.
A book could laugh with him in spite of all his problems.
Now, let's see.
Didn't fish.
You all didn't go fishing.
You didn't go hunting.
While you were in College Station, did you all take many vacations?
Well, we took vacations.
We usually tried to go someplace where nobody knew us.
Was it primarily to visit family, or was it to go to... We had to visit family every year.
We had to come back and go to see our parents.
We had to do that.
One year, the year we built this house, we took the parkway and stopped at every place you could, and we cooked our meals along outside, and we went to...
They did motels where they had a swimming pool, and we went to the art museums...
And we'd do little things like that.
We went to the Outer Banks, went up and saw the pageant up there.
This is the type of family thing we did.
Saw the pageant, and then we came down to Outer Banks with the children there where they had their wild horses and so forth.
And he never called his office here.
He would call my sister in the evening in Cincinnati and tell her where we were in case something happened in one of the families.
He would report in.
to Ohio instead of Clemson.
He never made any contact with the university while we were away.
We went to Florida one year, and then I went to the circus museum.
That's the type of vacation we would take with the children.
And he and I just started traveling when
When he died, just going off on a nice vacation.
In May, we joined Hugh and Pinky in London and toured London before he died in October.
London and Scotland.
And one year when we lived in Houston, I said, let's go to New York and see the Picasso exhibit.
And he acted like I didn't say a word.
So I called up Pinky and I said, would you like to go to New York to see the Pecanasol exhibit?
She said, yes, we'll go when he's in Colorado.
And he could tell the telephone conversation that she was going with me.
And I said, do you want to go?
And he said, well, you've already picked a date when Hugh's not going to be available.
And so as it turned out, we couldn't get tickets for that weekend.
So that looked like he was off.
And then they added a week.
So we added a week, and we went to New York.
We were the last people to see the Picasso exhibit.
But we went to six Broadway plays.
And we had a wonderful time.
You know, what I'm saying is our vacations were not anything fancy, but they were fun.
But Jack was always quiet.
You were around him to know that.
He didn't stir up anything.
No, but he always had that good sense of humor.
He was just easy to be with.
Yes.
You know, for me, he was just that part of me that was easy to be with.
If we were together, that's all it meant.
That's all it mattered.
You know, I don't know how to tell you all that.
You're going to edit this stuff out, I hope.
No, what we're going to do is try to get this typed up, give it back to you for you to correct, to...

edit to add subtract what i hope you will do will be to add to it to fill in any gaps and so let's see and let's uh let's try to draw it to an end as you look back on those texas a m years what do you think were the most significant williams the two of you the most significant williams contributions to what a m is
what it has become.
Well, I don't feel like I made any.
I just kept peace and family.
And I felt like his biggest contribution was his staff, the people that he selected to put the programs together.
And that's Jack's biggest contribution.
He knows how to do that.
I think it's natural for him to not want credit for himself, but to be able to pick a team.
Do you agree with that?
Well, I think you're being too modest
I hope that the team was pretty good, but it was the leader of that team that really mattered to all of us.
I felt like he was very fortunate in the people that were there that he could get to work with him and put his programs together.
And I don't know where, some of the things, I don't know whose idea it was.
The Galveston program, who's that?
John Calhoun's, I assume.
Don't you think that he was his?
No.

you know, different people made their contributions, and he was willing to follow through and develop anything he could, but his biggest contribution was the people that he worked with, you know, that he gave the responsibility to.
In 1976, when the board of directors, I guess they were still called, we'll call them regents now, when they were going to recreate the system, and there needed then to be a president appointed,
Whom did Dr. Williams recommend be the president?
No, no, no.
Dr. Williams is going to be the chancellor.
They're recreating that job.
But who did he recommend?
He recommended John Calhoun.
You know that.
Well, that's what I thought.
Yeah, you know that.
He knew all these wonderful people in publishing.
We're talking about Frank Wardlow now.
Okay.
He knew all these wonderful people in publishing.
And we would be invited over for dinner and sit there and have an evening with all these marvelous people.
You know, it was just fascinating to these people that he knew and to hear Frank Wardlow tell his stories.
He was one of the most entertaining people I had ever heard.
One of the most interesting men I've ever heard.
And that marvelous South Carolina accent.
Uh-huh.
Uh-huh.
It was just fabulous to listen to.
And I went to his service up here when it happened.
And somebody said, how many people were there?
The McCauley's were with me.
